english:
  title: Farewell Ode to Prime Minister Kang Maeng-gyeong's Journey to Jinsan to Visit His Mother
  author: Kwon Ram
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the winter of the kyongsinnyear, when Prime Minister Kang Maeng-gyeong of Jinsan was to journey to Jinyang to pay respects to his mother, His Majesty specially bestowed a longevity banquet upon the Lady and moreover a celebration of comfort, commanding his eldest son, the Inspector of the Remonstrance Office, to accompany him. Such grace and honor were without measure.

    On the tenth day, the auspicious date arrived. Left Minister Shin Suk-ju of Koryong, Censor-General Hwang Su-sin of Namwon, and Left Counselor Yi Seung-son, leading their retinues, gathered at the Prime Minister's residence for the farewell feast. I, unworthy, took my place among such luminaries. As the wine grew warm and spirits rose, there came also Chong Chang-son of Bongwon, Pak Chong-u of Unseong, Hwang Chi-sin the Vice-President, Pak Won-haeng the Minister of Punishments, Ku Chi-kwan the Minister of Appointments, Kim Chil the Vice-Minister of War, and Yu Hyo-chom the Vice-Minister of Works. The ceremonies of toasting completed, we dispersed as night fell. Glorious indeed was the gathering!

    Once, Ouyang Xiu composed an inscription for Han Wei-gong's Hall of Returning in Daylight, writing: "To rise through office to the rank of general and minister, to gain wealth and fortune and return to one's homeland—this is what the human heart desires, and the same in all ages." Yet our Minister Kang, having early excelled in the grand examinations and served in both capital and provinces, achieved renown as a celebrated official. When our Sage King established his reign, he entered the ranks of meritorious subjects and, before reaching the age of knowing heaven's will, ascended to the highest position, becoming first among all honored servants. And his mother, blessed with vigorous health, enjoys honor in her native place. What can surpass the glory and filial piety of this journey?

    We wonder if even the great minister Wei-gong received such benevolence from a sage king as our Minister Kang. We wonder if even Wei-gong's mother enjoyed such vigor and honor as does our Minister's. Thus this journey is far more than mere return of a great official to his homeland—it is truly what the ages have rarely witnessed. I am moved by our Lord's reverence for his meritorious servants, and I marvel at our Minister's glorification through honoring his mother. I record here what these eyes have seen, that it may shine for those who come after. I append my humble verse to escort his traveling dust.
  footnotes:
    - Ouyang Xiu (歐陽修) was a renowned Song dynasty scholar-official whose "Record of the Hall of Returning in Daylight" (晝錦堂記) became an archetypal text celebrating virtuous officials who return honored to their hometowns.
    - Han Wei-gong (韓魏公, Han Qi) was a celebrated Northern Song prime minister whose exemplary conduct and filial piety made him a model for later officials.
    - The 'kyongsin year' (庚辰) appears in the lunar calendar approximately every 60 years; this likely refers to 1460 during the reign of King Sejo.
    - Jinyang (晉陽) is an alternate name for Jinsan (晉山), suggesting the Minister's ancestral homeland.
